"1320","18 March 1292":"18 March 1292","1328":"1328","Lamington, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lamington, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland","Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wlliam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Wlliam Baliol of Cavers, 1st of Lamington was born in 1290, in Berwickshire, Scotland, his father, Alexander de Balliol of Cavers, was 48 and his mother, Isabelle De Dover of Chilham, was 43. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Wallace Heiress of Lamington. He died in 1357, in Lamington, Lanarkshire, Scotland, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1290–1357":"1290–1357","1271–1312":"1271–1312","1273–1327":"1273–1327","1274–1328":"1274–1328","1275–1290":"1275–1290","1295–1320":"1295–1320","1320–1389":"1320–1389","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1247–1292":"1247–1292","1242":"1242","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1273":"1273","1271":"1271","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1357":"1357","1247":"1247","1389":"1389","1312":"1312","1320":"1320","18 March 1292":"18. märts 1292","1328":"1328","Lamington, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Lamington, Lanarkshi